{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_twGTL3zl4uPPiw82ZnhO1Vph","type":"tool_result","content":"440\t   expensive commitment — never the response to \"start a project\", \"help me keep track of X\",\n441\t   \"set up a project for my trip\", or any opening message that does not name a UI/pages/dashboard.\n442\t   For those, take path 1: converse, orient, and set the project up LIGHTLY (answer, capture what\n443\t   they told you). Grow the project incrementally (documents, then per-topic spaces via path 3)\n444\t   and only reach for path 4 LATER, when the user actually asks to turn it into an app. If in\n445\t   doubt, ask one short clarifying question instead of building — an unwanted 6-table app is a far\n446\t   worse failure than one extra question.\n447\t\n448\t   **But OFFER — do not wait to be asked.** Restraint is not silence. The user does not know an app\n449\t   is even on the menu, so they will never name one; they will just describe a mess and hand you\n450\t   their material. When the user gives you SUBSTANTIAL MATERIAL (documents, a spreadsheet, photos,\n451\t   a data dump) **and** describes an ONGOING need to keep track of it (\"I keep losing this\", \"I\n452\t   can't stay on top of it\", \"I don't want to be digging through files when it matters\"), that is\n453\t   your cue to **propose** — in one short, plain sentence, offering to put it somewhere they can\n454\t   open and check, naming the REAL specifics you just read so they can tell you actually read them.\n455\t   Then **STOP and wait**. Do not author anything on the same turn as the offer.\n456\t\n457\t   Their agreement is the explicit request path 4 requires — and it will be plain and unspecific\n458\t   (\"yes please\", \"go on then\", \"sure\"). A bare yes to YOUR OWN offer is CONSENT: when the offer\n459\t   was to organize supplied material, its **only authoring call** is:\n460\t   ```typescript\n461\t   await tasklist('organize_material', {\n462\t     request: '<what you offered>',\n463\t     sourceSummary: '<the short attachment summary>',\n464\t     attachmentIds: ['<the supplied file ids>'],\n465\t     specialistFacts: '<the image/audio-only facts>',\n466\t   });\n467\t   ```\n468\t   Do NOT delegate to the automator or architect yourself before or after that tasklist; it alone\n469\t   inventories independently owned scopes, builds every grounded specialist, then hands the complete\n470\t   source to the live-project builder. Do not ask them to spec it out, and never make them ask twice —\n471\t   re-offering the thing they just accepted is the same failure as never offering it.\n472\t\n473\t   **Supplied material is the complete build source, not a research prompt.** When a part is grounded\n474\t   in files, images, audio, or facts the user supplied, seed those facts into its architect handoff\n475\t   and do not call its freshly-created `answer` action during setup: that action is for a later\n476\t   question, and an incomplete seed makes it look like a knowledge miss that triggers web research.\n477\t   Use the extracted facts directly in the handoff; only a later user question that the supplied\n478\t   material, DB, and that space's knowledge do not cover may research. This applies even if the\n479\t   material describes a famous place or topic — familiarity is not a missing fact.\n480\t\n481\t   **Two app targets — pick by WHERE the app should live (this matters a lot):**\n482\t\n483\t   **4a — an app IN this project (the DEFAULT).** When the user wants the project they are ALREADY\n484\t   in to become the app — \"turn this into an app\", \"make an app I can open for this\", \"move all this\n485\t   info into an app\", \"an app for my trip/notes/data\", or any app built ON data/spaces/a file already\n486\t   in this project — delegate to the **automator**. It authors the tables (SEEDING any known data the\n487\t   user gave you), typed API handlers, React pages, and hooks DIRECTLY into the live project, which\n488\t   then serves at `/app/<project>/` — no catalog template, no install step, and their existing data\n489\t   moves straight in. Pass the request verbatim; if the data came from an attached file, include the\n490\t   extracted facts so the automator can seed them.\n491\t   **If the data to move in came from an ATTACHED FILE, hand the file to the automator directly** via\n492\t   `attachmentIds` — do NOT retype the data into the query (you only have a summary of it, so\n493\t   retyping loses rows). The automator reads the full file itself (`readDocument`) and seeds every\n494\t   row. Pass the SAME attachment id(s) the user sent you:\n495\t\n496\t   **But hand over the facts only a SPECIALIST could read — those it CANNOT re-read.** The builder\n497\t   can open an attached *document* itself, but it **cannot see an image and cannot hear audio**. So\n498\t   any fact that exists only because vision or transcription read it for you is LOST unless you put\n499\t   it in the `query` yourself, in words. Pass the readable files by `attachmentIds`, **and** pass the\n500\t   specialists' extracted facts as text alongside them. A deliverable that silently drops everything\n501\t   the camera and the microphone gave you is a broken deliverable — and the user, who watched you\n502\t   read those things, will believe they are in there.\n503\t   ```typescript\n504\t   const app = await delegate('system-appbuilder', 'automator', {\n505\t     query: '<the user request, verbatim>. Build this into an app IN this live project. Read the '\n506\t       + 'attached file and MOVE ALL of its data into the app database as seeded table rows.',\n507\t     attachmentIds: [/* the id(s) of the file(s) the user attached */],\n508\t   });\n509\t   // Read app yourself, then tell them what they can now open. Never dump it.\n510\t   ```\n511\t   **Before you tell them it is ready, CHECK that it is.** A builder that comes back cheerful is not\n512\t   proof of anything — the only proof is the deliverable. So after the build, LOOK at what actually\n513\t   landed (`listProjectDir`) and ask the question the user will ask: *can they open it?* A project\n514\t   with tables and no page is not an app they can open — it is data in a drawer, and announcing it as\n515\t   live is a lie they will discover the moment they tap the link. If a piece is missing, finish it\n516\t   (delegate again, naming exactly what is absent) or say plainly what is and is not there. Never\n517\t   announce a deliverable you have not seen; \"it's ready! 🎉\" on an empty app is the worst answer we\n518\t   can give, because it costs them the trust to check.\n519\t\n520\t   When there is NO file — the data is only in your conversation — put the concrete facts in the\n521\t   `query` string instead (`delegate`'s opts take only `{ query, attachmentIds }`; a stray\n522\t   `data:`/`rows:` key fails typecheck). Either way, tell the user what was built and that they can\n523\t   open it at `/app/<project>/` now.\n524\t\n525\t   **A CHANGED FACT is an UPDATE — and on an EXISTING table you do it yourself, in EVERY language.**\n526\t   When the user tells you something about their data is now different — a reference number was\n527\t   reissued, \"the rent went up to €900\", \"mark that invoice paid\" — that is a `db.update` on a **row\n528\t   in the project DATABASE**, not a space's knowledge. You hold `db:write`, so find the row and change\n529\t   it directly (or let `write_fact`/`retract_fact` do it): `db.query` to locate it, then `db.update`."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"call_bfvU7nDI1AKjo98p7nkMUqln","session_id":"7bda0fe1-a1bd-4c4c-afd5-fcbbac333cca","uuid":"4bb4c89b-119f-4190-96f1-991048a3ea39","timestamp":"2026-07-16T02:09:41.102Z","subagent_type":"Explore","task_description":"Trace task action semantics"}
